---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import '../../styles/global.css';
import '../../styles/course.css';
import LessonPage from '../../components/course/LessonPage';
import GatePanel from '../../components/assessment/GatePanel';
---

<BaseLayout title="Where Time Goes in an LLM">
  <LessonPage lessonId="L32" client:load>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Question</div>
      <div class="lesson-question">Where does time go during inference?</div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Intuition</div>
      <p>
        An LLM inference request runs through dozens of layers, each containing several operators: attention projections (Q, K, V, O), attention score computation, FFN up/gate/down projections, normalization, and finally an output-head projection. Not all operators cost the same amount of time.
      </p>
      <p>
        The <strong>matrix multiplications</strong> in the projections dominate. Attention projections, FFN projections, and the output head together account for the vast majority of compute. Normalization and elementwise operations (residual adds, activation functions) are comparatively cheap.
      </p>
      <p>
        But the <em>mix</em> changes between <strong>prefill</strong> and <strong>decode</strong> (the two phases you learned in L27–L28). During prefill, the model processes many tokens at once, so all projections run as large matrix-matrix multiplies (GEMM) and attention score computation over the full prompt can also be significant. During decode, only one token is processed per step, so projections become matrix-vector multiplies (GEMV) and the attention score computation is much smaller per step. The relative cost of loading model weights from memory becomes more important in decode.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Toy Example</div>
      <div class="toy-example">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">
          Rough operator time breakdown for a single layer (illustrative):
        </p>
        <div style="font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm);">
          <div style="margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">
            <div style="color: var(--ink-ghost); margin-bottom: var(--space-1);">Prefill (512 tokens):</div>
            <div style="padding-left: var(--space-4);">
              <div><span style="color: var(--sem-attention);">QKV projections:</span> 30%</div>
              <div><span style="color: var(--sem-attention);">Attention scores + softmax:</span> 15%</div>
              <div><span style="color: var(--sem-attention);">Output projection:</span> 10%</div>
              <div><span style="color: var(--sem-ffn);">FFN (up + gate + down):</span> 40%</div>
              <div><span style="color: var(--ink-tertiary);">Norm + residual:</span> 5%</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div>
            <div style="color: var(--ink-ghost); margin-bottom: var(--space-1);">Decode (1 token):</div>
            <div style="padding-left: var(--space-4);">
              <div><span style="color: var(--sem-attention);">QKV projections:</span> 25%</div>
              <div><span style="color: var(--sem-attention);">Attention (KV cache read):</span> 20%</div>
              <div><span style="color: var(--sem-attention);">Output projection:</span> 10%</div>
              <div><span style="color: var(--sem-ffn);">FFN (up + gate + down):</span> 40%</div>
              <div><span style="color: var(--ink-tertiary);">Norm + residual:</span> 5%</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-top: var(--space-3);">
          Exact percentages vary by model and hardware, but the pattern is consistent: projections and FFN dominate both phases.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Why Projections Dominate</div>
      <p>
        A projection is a matrix multiply: [n_tokens, d_in] &times; [d_in, d_out]. The number of multiply-add operations
        is n_tokens &times; d_in &times; d_out. For a single FFN up-projection with d_model = 4096 and d_ff = 16384:
      </p>
      <div style="font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary); padding-left: var(--space-4); margin: var(--space-2) 0;">
        1 token: 4096 &times; 16384 = 67M FLOPs<br/>
        512 tokens: 512 &times; 4096 &times; 16384 = 34.4B FLOPs
      </div>
      <p>
        One layer has multiple projections: Q, K, V, output (attention side) plus up, gate, down (FFN side). That is
        7 large matrix multiplies per layer. A 32-layer model does 224 matrix multiplies per forward pass. The
        normalization, residual adds, and activation functions are elementwise — they touch the same data but do far
        fewer operations per element.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is why performance optimization for LLMs is largely about optimizing matrix multiplies. If you can make
        <code>ggml_mul_mat</code> 20% faster, you speed up the entire model by close to 20%.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">How to Read a Profile</div>
      <p>
        When you profile an LLM inference run, you will see a list of operators with their execution times. The right
        way to read it:
      </p>
      <ol style="list-style: decimal; padding-left: var(--space-5); margin: var(--space-3) 0;">
        <li style="padding: var(--space-1) 0; font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
          <strong>Look at the distribution first.</strong> What fraction of time is in matrix multiplies vs everything else?
          If matmuls are 90%, optimizing softmax (3%) is a waste of effort.
        </li>
        <li style="padding: var(--space-1) 0; font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
          <strong>Classify the bottleneck.</strong> Is the time spent doing arithmetic (compute-bound) or waiting for
          data (memory-bound)? The answer depends on whether this is prefill or decode and on the shapes involved.
        </li>
        <li style="padding: var(--space-1) 0; font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
          <strong>Then drill into individual operators.</strong> Only after you know the bottleneck class does it make
          sense to look at which specific matmul is slowest.
        </li>
      </ol>
      <p>
        The most common beginner mistake: looking at the single hottest function and assuming "that is the problem."
        Often the hottest function is doing exactly what it should — it is just the largest operation. The real question
        is whether it is running at the hardware's capability for that operation type.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Shapes</div>
      <div class="shape-card">
        <div>Each projection: [n_tokens, d_in] &times; [d_in, d_out]</div>
        <div>Prefill: n_tokens is large &rarr; big GEMM</div>
        <div>Decode: n_tokens = 1 &rarr; GEMV</div>
        <div style="color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-top: var(--space-2);">
          The same weight matrix is used in both phases, but the workload shape changes completely.
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Math</div>
      <p>Total FLOPs per layer (approximate, for one token in decode):</p>
      <div style="font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm); background: var(--surface-3); padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4); border-radius: var(--radius-sm); margin: var(--space-3) 0;">
        <div style="color: var(--sem-attention);">QKV projections: 3 &times; 2 &times; d_model &times; d_model</div>
        <div style="color: var(--sem-attention);">Output projection: 2 &times; d_model &times; d_model</div>
        <div style="color: var(--sem-ffn);">FFN (SwiGLU): 3 &times; 2 &times; d_model &times; d_ffn</div>
        <div style="color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-top: var(--space-2);">
          For a 7B model: d_model ~ 4096, d_ffn ~ 11008 &rarr; FFN alone is ~135M FLOPs per token per layer.
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Implementation Hook</div>
      <div class="impl-hook">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
          In <code>llama.cpp</code>, each layer's operators are built in <code>src/llama-graph.cpp</code> via functions like <code>build_attn()</code> and <code>build_ffn()</code>. Profiling with <code>GGML_PERF</code> or external tools reveals that <code>ggml_mul_mat</code> calls dominate the trace in both prefill and decode.
        </p>
        <div class="file-path">src/llama-graph.cpp &mdash; build_attn(), build_ffn()</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Performance Hook</div>
      <div class="perf-hook">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
          Knowing where time goes tells you where to look first. If prefill is slow, the large GEMM projections and attention-score computation are the suspects. If decode is slow, model-weight loading (memory bandwidth) for each projection is usually the bottleneck since only one token is processed at a time.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Check Yourself</div>
      <GatePanel
        client:load
        lessonId="L32"
        gateStrength="hard"
        questions={[
          {
            id: 'L32-q1',
            type: 'single_choice',
            prompt: 'During prefill with a long prompt, which operators are likely to dominate wall-clock time?',
            tag: 'reasoning',
            choices: [
              { id: 'a', text: 'RMSNorm and residual additions', isCorrect: false },
              { id: 'b', text: 'Matrix multiply projections (QKV, FFN) and attention score computation', isCorrect: true },
              { id: 'c', text: 'Token embedding lookups', isCorrect: false },
            ],
            explanation: 'Prefill processes many tokens at once. The large matrix-matrix multiplies in QKV projections, FFN projections, and the attention score computation over the full prompt dominate. Norm and residual are elementwise and comparatively cheap.',
          },
          {
            id: 'L32-q2',
            type: 'single_choice',
            prompt: 'Why does the operator mix differ between prefill and decode?',
            tag: 'reasoning',
            choices: [
              { id: 'a', text: 'Different model weights are used in each phase', isCorrect: false },
              { id: 'b', text: 'Prefill processes many tokens at once (large matrices), while decode processes one token at a time (vectors)', isCorrect: true },
              { id: 'c', text: 'Decode skips the FFN layers', isCorrect: false },
            ],
            explanation: 'The same operators run in both phases, but prefill batches many tokens into large matrix multiplies while decode processes a single token, turning projections into matrix-vector operations with very different performance characteristics.',
          },
        ]}
      />
    </div>

  </LessonPage>
</BaseLayout>
